vements been unable to reproduce their political culture beyond one or two generations? In a postscript, he compares the difficulties of contemporary secularism to the successful establishment of secular politics in the early American republic—thereby making an argument for American exceptionalism but gravely noting that we may be less exceptional today.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aDemocracyzDeveloping countriesvCase studies. 0aPolitical culturezDeveloping countriesvCase studies. 0aReligious fundamentalismzDeveloping countriesvCase studies. 0aSecularismzDeveloping countriesvCase studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Freedom.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertYale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015z97831106725030 cprintz978030018780940uhttps://doi.org/10.12987/978030021391140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780300213911423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780300213911/original  a978-3-11-067250-3  Yale University Press Complete eBook-Package 2014-2015c2014d2015  aEBA_FAO  aEBA_UCA_YUP  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aZDB-23-UCY